Europe Needs to Restart Its Immigration Policy
Brussels—More than 900 migrants attempting to reach Europe have drowned in the Mediterranean this year.
Meanwhile, the rescue ships Open Arms and Ocean Viking have been searching for safe ports where their passengers can disembark all summer.
Refugee and migrant camps on the Greek island of Lesbos are overcrowded, and conditions in other camps in Libya are similarly dire.
Turkey has torn up the 2016 agreement meant to prevent migrants from entering the EU.
Although Europe wants to help migrants and respects international law, it does not want to be overcrowded.
In 2015-16, the number of refugees and migrants flowing into the EU surged — many of them fleeing the war in Syria — which greatly affected trust within the EU.
The massive influx of migrants eroded governments' confidence in the management of the EU's external borders and asylum, and also highlighted the futility of cooperation with countries of origin of migrants.
As a result, migration has become a political football, a favorite topic for populists.
Under the leadership of President von der Leyen, the new European Commission must regain control of the migration issue while respecting the dignity of those seeking a better life.
To this end, the EU needs to revise its policies in four areas and mobilize member states to take action in the interest of Europe.
First, the EU must urgently secure its external borders, which is a prerequisite for keeping its internal borders open.
Countries where any people can freely move internally, including the United States, India, China, Switzerland, and Russia, would not outsource the control of external borders to a state or region.
Controlling the EU's external borders must be a collective task and also a national task.
The EU Border and Coast Guard Agency Frontex must be further strengthened and should be deployed with joint security forces by member states — including coastal areas and airports.
The EU must also restart Operation Sophia, targeting illegal migration in the Mediterranean.
Secondly, Europe needs to treat economic migrants and asylum seekers separately.
Mixing them up has led the asylum system to the brink of collapse; treating them separately helps ensure that migrants concerned about their safety can voice their concerns while their rights are protected.
Addressing the real economic and social needs of the EU requires an effective blue or green card policy targeting economic migrants, as well as the implementation of overall immigration targets.
These measures must not be delayed until the next immigration crisis occurs.
To achieve this, the EU must break the taboo.
First, the number of economic immigrants entering the EU labor market must be recognized as a matter of common interest.
Second, policies must clearly define which immigrants are desirable.
Third, member states must address what EU assistance is needed to ensure a smooth immigration process.
Finally, visas and work permits must be put on the table to facilitate the return of illegal immigrants to their countries of origin.
Indeed, according to the EU treaties, member states need to manage immigration from outside the EU themselves.
However, if governments reach an agreement on overall EU immigration targets, it would be a significant progress.
In turn, member states could specify the source countries and specific requirements for economic immigrants they want, as well as the EU budget resources needed to accommodate them.
This way, the right to accept immigrants would become a privilege rather than a burden.
For example, Canada has long implemented a proactive immigration policy, selecting immigrants based on criteria such as country of origin, skill level, and age.
Europe can also do this.
Third, the EU needs to improve its asylum system.
First, the one-size-fits-all requirement of forcibly distributing asylum seekers within the EU must be abandoned.
This requirement undermines the atmosphere within the EU, but it could still be feasible if the border, asylum, and immigration systems are fully effective.
Moreover, it is not reasonable to expect front-line EU member states to solve the problem of illegal immigrants crossing external borders on their own.
The camps are already overcrowded, and migrants are subjected to abuse by the authorities or driven northwards.
The responsibility of the first member state reached by the migrants must be reinforced by EU solidarity.
The EU must also provide experts and funding to streamline the behavior and management capacity of national asylum agencies.
Only in this way can national decisions be respected throughout the Schengen area, ensuring the integrity of the cross-border travel zone.
Once the behavior and management capacity of national asylum agencies are streamlined, the asylum application processing procedures can also be shared among member states.
Fourth, the EU should establish stronger mutually beneficial cooperation with countries of origin and transit countries.
These links are crucial in order to repatriate immigrants who are legally prohibited from entering the EU back to their countries of origin.
To ensure cooperation, the EU should mobilize all diplomatic policy tools, including development aid and investment funds, as well as programs in the areas of security, trade, energy, agriculture, fisheries, climate action, aviation, and health.
The EU's immigration objectives, as well as skills cooperation aimed at preparing for European jobs, can be offered to third countries eager for stable remittances.
At the same time, the EU must address the root causes of migration.
This includes the population explosion in sub-Saharan Africa; climate change affecting food security; outbreaks of infectious diseases; ethnic conflicts; and a shortage of job opportunities.
The EU's aid should focus on reshaping stability and reducing risks through support for security, community resilience, and good governance.
Success in this area can make investments safer, release private and domestic finances, thereby achieving national economic growth, job creation, and providing alternatives to migration.
The new European Commission has an opportunity to move the EU away from instinctive reactions to the migration crisis and towards a more coherent and sustained approach, whether internally or externally.
We must never miss this opportunity.
